<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="116" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,1976,2037]" lastBlockId="15.[151,1437,151,683]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="116" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1976,2001]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The external characters of the species are characterized by: the male pectinations are short than the diameter of the shaft; the vertex is black, and diffused with white on the posterior margin; the hind tarsus of the male is about two-fifths length of the tibia; the forewing R5 is shortly stalked with R2-4 or separate; the ocellus of fore- and hind wings are incomplete, the former is narrow band-like, covered by pale yellowish brown mixed with silvery scales, the latter is indistinct, cosists of two silvery lines and sparse yellowish brown scales centrally. The diagnosis of the male genitalia could be seen under 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Warren" authorityYear="1897" box="[742,1030,263,287]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Problepsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="delphiaria" subSpecies="auriculifera">
<emphasis box="[742,1030,263,287]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">P. delphiaria auriculifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The female genitalia are unique in the small semicircular lamella postvaginalis and the short partly sclerotized ductus bursae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
