<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="116" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,683]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,478,503]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Remarks.</emphasis>
Prout (1938) mentioned this species shows the venational transitions between 
<taxonomicName authority="Guenee, 1858" authorityName="Guenee" authorityYear="1858" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Somatina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1228,1334,479,502]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Somatina</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Guenee" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" refId="ref23979" refString="Guenee, M. A. (1858) Boisduval, J. B. A. D. &amp; Guenee, M. A., Histoire Naturelle des Insectes (Species General des Lepidopteres). Vol. 10. Roret, Paris, 584 pp., 22. pls" type="book" year="1858">Guenée, 1858</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lederer" authorityYear="1853" box="[279,398,515,539]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Problepsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[279,398,515,539]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Problepsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Later, 
<bibRefCitation author="Sihvonen" box="[502,699,514,539]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" refId="ref24947" refString="Sihvonen, P. (2005) Phylogeny and classification of the Scopulini moths (Lepidoptera: Geometridae, Sterrhinae). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 143, 473 - 530." type="journal article" year="2005">Sihvonen (2005)</bibRefCitation>
mentinoned the species should probably be combined with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lederer" authorityYear="1853" box="[151,270,551,575]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Problepsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,270,551,575]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Problepsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as it has weakly developed ocellus and slivery scales. In our study, we found this species well agrees with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lederer" authorityYear="1853" box="[212,331,587,611]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Problepsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[212,331,587,611]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Problepsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the wing patterns and the genitalia, especially the slivery (opalescent) scales on the wings. 
<bibRefCitation author="Hausmann" box="[151,355,623,647]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" refId="ref24121" refString="Hausmann, A. (2004) The Geometrid Moths of Europe. Vol. 2. Sterrhinae. Apollo Books, Stenstrup, 600 pp." type="book" year="2004">Hausmann (2004)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned the structure and arrangement of the opalescent scales are unique in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[1284,1433,622,647]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Geometridae</taxonomicName>
. Therefore we transfer this species to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lederer" authorityYear="1853" box="[564,683,659,683]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Problepsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[564,683,659,683]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Problepsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
